04472nam a22006255i 9780822379515DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223795157 a10.1515/97808223795152doi  a(DE-B1597)554365  a(OCoLC)891395261  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS153.N5bF38 1999eb 7aLIT0040402bisacsh04a810.9/896073222  aHU 17282rvk0(DE-625)rvk/53761:1 aFavor, J. Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAuthentic Blackness :bThe Folk in the New Negro Renaissance /cJ. Martin Favor. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Discourses of Black Identity: The Elements of Authenticity -- t2 For a Mess of Pottage: James Weldon Johnson's Ex-Colored Man as (In)authentic Man -- t3 "Colored; cold. Wrong somewhere?': Jean Toomer's Cane -- t4 A Clash of Birthrights: Nella Larsen, the Feminine, and African American Identity -- t5 Color, Culture, and the Nature of Race: George S. Schuyler's Black No More -- t6 The Possibilities of Multiplicity: Community, Tradition, and African American Subject Positions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat constitutes "blackness" in American culture? And who gets to define whether or not someone is truly African American? Is a struggling hip-hop artist more "authentic" than a conservative Supreme Court justice? In Authentic Blackness J. Martin Favor looks to the New Negro Movement-also known as the Harlem Renaissance-to explore early challenges to the idea that race is a static category.Authentic Blackness looks at the place of the "folk"-those African Americans "furthest down," in the words of Alain Locke-and how the representation of the folk and the black middle class both spurred the New Negro Movement and became one of its most serious points of contention. Drawing on vernacular theories of African American literature from such figures as Henry Louis Gates Jr. and Houston Baker as well as theorists Judith Butler and Stuart Hall, Favor looks closely at the work of four Harlem Renaissance fiction writers: James Weldon Johnson, Nella Larsen, George Schuyler, and Jean Toomer. Arguing that each of these writers had, at best, an ambiguous relationship to African American folk culture, Favor demonstrates how they each sought to redress the notion of a fixed black identity. Authentic Blackness illustrates how "race" has functioned as a type of performative discourse, a subjectivity that simultaneously builds and conceals its connections with such factors as class, gender, sexuality, and geography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGroup identity in literature. 0aHarlem Renaissance. 0aRace in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822379515zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822379515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822379515.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles